<sect1><title>Yags</title>

<para> 
Yags is Another Game System, one that is meant to be generic
and modular. Generic because it should be usuable with a
number of different backgrounds and genres, and modular
because the rules are designed to be pluggable and
exchangable - it's not meant to be another GURPS, where
one size fits all.
</para>
</sect1>

<sect1><title>The Basic System</title>
<para>
This chapter gives a brief tour of the Yags system, explaining 
terminology, and giving a description of the basic conventions 
used.
</para>

<sect2><title>Dice Conventions</title>
<para>
As with most role playing games, Yags uses dice as a means of 
randomly determining the outcome of many events. The only type 
of die used is the d20.
</para>
<para>
Normally, a die is used to determine success or failure when a 
character (or creature) uses a skill or ability. The level of 
their ability is found, and 1d20 is rolled and added to it.
</para>

<sect3><title>Fumbles</title>
<para>
A fumble normally occurs on an ability roll if the total die 
roll is 1. Under some situations which warrant extra chances of 
a fumble, a roll of 2 (or even higher) may cause a fumble to 
occur.
</para>
</sect3>
</sect2>

