<sect2><title>Attributes</title>
<para>
Attributes are the basic defining characteristics of any character 
in Yags. There are eight attributes - strength, stamina, agility,
dexterity, perception, intelligence, charisma and will - and 
all characters will have them at some level.
</para>
<para>
An average value for any attribute for a human adult is considered 
to be three, and most people will have an attribute between two 
and four. The minimum value for a human is one, and the maximum 
for starting characters is five. Ultimately however, there is no 
limit to how high attributes can go, through anything above six 
will be legendary.
</para>
<para>
An attribute of zero indicates that a creature has no ability in 
that area, and cannot even attempt tasks which would require it. 
No creature will ever have an attribute below zero, and humans 
never have attributes below one.
</para>
<para>
Attributes can change over a character's life, and it is possible 
to improve attributes through training.
</para>

<sect3><title>Strength</title>
<para>
The strength of a character is a measure of their physical 
toughness and ability to hurt, break and lift things independent 
of their size. Strength is most often used in combat, where it 
helps a character to both absorb damage, and to do it to other 
people.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Stamina</title>
<para>
A character's stamina is a measure of their physical endurance, 
fitness and general ability to cope with fatigue and physical 
pain. Strength and agility will allow a character to run fast, 
but stamina is what keeps them running after everyone else has 
collapsed from exhaustion. Though it is strength which is used 
to resist damage, stamina is used to stay alive and conscious 
once damage has been taken.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Agility</title>
<para>
Agility is how quick and agile a character is when performing 
acrobatic and athletic feats. An agile character will hit first 
in combat, and will be able to jump further and run faster than 
less agile characters. Agility is also used for general brawling, 
though not for melee and missile weapons.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Dexterity</title>
<para>
The dexterity of a character defines their hand-eye coordination, 
sleight-of-hand, and skill with melee weapons. Pick pockets and 
warriors need a good dexterity.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Perception</title>
<para>
Perception is a measure of a character's senses. Perceptive 
characters notice things that others will miss, making it a 
useful attribute for hunters, scouts and thieves. It is also 
used with social skills to detect emotions and lies in other 
people.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Intelligence</title>
<para>
A character's intelligence is their reasoning, common sense, 
memory and intuition. It is not their knowledge, since this 
comes from skills, but an intelligent character will be 
able to better use what they know by applying it to new 
situations (and also by remembering what they know better).
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Charisma</title>
<para>
How charismatic a character is defines how others will 
relate to them. A very charismatic character will find 
others helpful, friendly, and generally well disposed 
towards them. An uncharismatic character will make only 
enemies. Charisma is not a measure of physical beauty. 
It is however, a measure of how a character sounds, so a 
charismatic character will tend to have a pleasant voice.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Will</title>
<para>
A character's will is their strength of mind, general 
stubbornness and sense of purpose. A strong willed 
person will know what they want, and who they are. They 
will be in control of their actions, not often allowing 
animal passions to get in the way. A low willed person 
will be more governed by the desires of the moment, often 
giving in to passion even when such is against their 
better judgement.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Size</title>
<para>
Characters and creatures also have a size attribute, 
which is a sort of pseudo-attribute, being treated 
differently to the other eight. The majority of adult 
humans will have a size of 5. Exceptionally large or 
small humans may have a size of 6 or 4 respectively.
</para>
<para>
The size attribute affects the amount of damage a 
creature can sustain (the number of body levels it has), 
and a few other combat statistics. Generally, it can be 
assumed to be 5 for most characters.
</para>
</sect3>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Skills</title>
<para>
A skill is something which can be learnt, and can only 
be gained with experience and training. Unless otherwise 
specified during character generation, all skills 
default to a score of zero.
</para>
<para>
When a skill is used, it is multiplied with a given 
attribute, to give the character's final ability score. 
Generally, neither attributes nor skills are used by 
themselves, they are always multiplied together first. 
There are some exceptions though, where the attribute 
is used by itself, multiply its value by four.
</para>
<para>
To make a skill check, the character's ability score is 
found, and 1d20 is rolled and added to it.
</para>
<para>
A skill of four is considered to be professional level, 
and someone with an average attribute of three and a 
skill at four would be able to accomplish moderate tasks 
with ease.
</para>

<sect3><title>Example Skill Levels</title>

<sect4><title>Unfamiliar (0)</title>
<para>
The character has no training in the skill, 
and has no knowledge about how to solve tasks requiring the 
skill.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Minimal (1)</title>
<para>
The character has some basic knowledge of the 
skill, but generally what ability they do have is still 
dwarfed by blind luck.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Basic (2)</title>
<para>
The character has some basic knowledge of the 
skill, and has used it on a regular basis. They can 'get by', 
and have a very good chance of completing simple tasks 
successfully.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Competent (3)</title>
<para>
The character should be able to succeed in tasks 
of moderate difficulty a good proportion of the time, and easy 
tasks should pose no problem.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Professional (4-5)</title>
<para>
The character is considered to be of 
professional skill, and will be suitable for entering into 
a career involving this skill. Many people in jobs which 
don't tax them a great deal will not exceed this level of 
skill. A village blacksmith, who spends his time making 
horseshoes and nails will not know much more after twenty 
years than he did out of apprenticeship. A warrior, who's 
very survival depends on his skill with the sword, and who 
practises every day against those of similar skill, may 
will exceed this level in a couple of years.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Seasoned (6-7)</title>
<para>
The character has used the skill extensively, 
and has much practical experience as well as theoretical 
knowledge. This is the cap for people who aren't stretching 
their skill to its limits. Many veteran warriors will have 
weapon skills this high. Craftsmen in large towns, who are 
competing against each other for custom with the quality of 
their work may well equal or exceed this level.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Exceptional (8-9)</title>
<para>
People with skills of this caliber will 
be rare, though not unheard of. There will be a few elite groups 
of people this skilled,  such as the huscarl of a major noble, 
but they will not be many.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Master (10-12)</title>
<para>
Those who achieve this level of skill will go 
down in history as master's of their craft. Such people will be 
very rare, and not randomly encountered.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Legendary (13-15)</title>
<para>
Only the very best, with 
extreme dedication to go with it, will achieve this level of skill.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Mythical (16+)</title>
<para>
This is considered the limit of human achievement.
Beyond Mythical. There is nothing in place which prevents 
skills of this magnitude, but they must be treated with a 
great deal of care.
</para>
</sect4>
</sect3>

