<sect1 status="alpha"><title>Passions (alpha)</title>

<para>
This section is currently optional, and under development. It totally
contradicts the rules on passions in the Advantages section which
follows.
</para>

<para>
Passions are a measure of a character's emotional traits, and to some
extent govern how the character acts in certain situations. Representing
such things with a game mechanic does mean that some control is taken
out of the hands of the player, and put into a die roll. However,
interpretation of the die roll is always up to the player, and further,
there are situations where character's would not do what a player
might want them to do. For example, facing some nameless terror could
instill fear (magical or natural) in a person. A game mechanic gives
the player the choice to design a character who is more likely to
resist such fears.
</para>

<para>
Passions are represented by four traits. These are treated like skills,
in that they can be improved after character generation. Each trait
represents a character's control over that aspect of their personality.
The higher the passion trait, then the higher the chance of the
character resisting that passion.
</para>

<para>
The four traits are Anger, Fear, Greed and Lust. Each defaults to four,
but can be purchased higher or lower with advantages and disadvantages.
Each of these is the ability to resist that passion, so a high Fear
trait would be had by a brave warrior.
</para>

<sect2><title>The Four Traits</title>

<sect3><title>Anger</title>
<para>
A character's ability to control anger enables him to resist taunting,
to not let blind range control his actions. A character with a low score
is easily provoked, and can find himself in fights he didn't want to get
in. It will be difficult to resist the opportunity to attack a hated
enemy, or to speak out against someone who is not liked.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Fear</title>
<para>
Fear is used to face danger without flinching. A character with a good
fear score can remain cool in the face of danger. This does not make them
foolhardy, and does not prevent them from retreating, but they will doso in an organised manner.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Greed</title>
<para>
Greed covers the desire for wealth and comfort, often at the expense of
other people.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Lust</title>
<para>
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Passion Checks</title>

<para>
When a situation comes up which warrents a passion check, the passion
trait is rolled with will, against a difficulty representative of the
situation. Some guidelines as to assigning difficulties are given below.
</para>

<para>
<variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
        <term>Very easy (10)</term>
        <listitem>
            Very few people would be tempted by this. A person would
            need to be very weak willed, or very prone to that passion
            in order to fail to resist.
        </listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Easy (15)</term>
        <listitem>
            Few people would fall to this, though slightly below average
            will, or slightly susceptible people would fail. A passion of
            2, and normal will, gives about 55% chance of resisting.
            Normal people have 90% chance of resisting.
        </listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Moderate (20)</term>
        <listitem>
            Most people will find this a challenge to resist. A decent
            bribe with little chance of come back, a dallience with no
            obvious long term risk, or something that's somewhat
            dangerous but with a good chance of success.
        </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
        
	<varlistentry>
	    <term>Challenging (25)</term>
	    <listitem>
	        A bit worse than moderate, and 60% will fail.
	    </listitem>
	</varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Difficulty (30)</term>
        <listitem>
            Majority of people will fail this. Something with a good
            chance of death with little benefit gained, a really good
            sexual offer with little or no chance of their being long
            term repurcussions (e.g. you're single), a lot of money
            for doing nothing, or a chance to kick an enemy when he's
            down really hard with no risk.
        </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
</variablelist>
</para>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Minor Passions</title>
<para>
Minor passions are traits which kick in under certain circumstances.
They might be love of a person, which helps the character stand his
ground when defending them. It could be loyalty, hatred or a weakness
for some vice.
</para>

<para>
A minor passion is considered to be an advantage (see below), and
modifies Will - for all intents they are edges and flaws. Most minor
passions will have a value of +1 (or -1), with a few being +2 (or -2).
In very rare cases, +3 (or -3) will be possible but this level cannot
be purchased at character generation.
</para>

<para>
For example, a character with love (family) as a minor passion would get
a +1 to will if rolling a fear check when defending them. If she had a
will of 3, and a Fear passion of 4, she would have an ability score of
(3+1) x 4 or 16, rather than the normal 12.
</para>

</sect2>

</sect1>




<sect1><title>Advantages</title>

<sect2><title>Passions</title>
<para>
Passions represent a character's stronger emotional 
traits, and range from +0 (no passion of particular note)
 to +5 (this passion consumes the character's life).
</para>
<para>
A character can have many passions, and are listed as 
being either of a general emotion (such as loyal, curious, 
cowardly) or as being directed towards a particular ideal or 
person (love of a friend, loyalty to a lord, hatred of a 
religion).
</para>
<para>
Passions of level +3 or higher are considered to be 
advantages or disadvantages, and must be paid for.
</para>

<sect3><title>Limits on Passions</title>
<para>
Generally, a character can only have one passion of +4 or 
higher, and if they have a passion of +5, then cannot 
have any other passion greater than +2.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Roleplaying Passions</title>
<para>
Though they are given as a game mechanic, passions 
should definitely be role played is the main area 
in which they are meant to be used. Passions of level 
+1 or +2 aren't greatly different from the norm (and 
hence aren't worth any points). A +3 passion is quite 
strong, and people who have been around you for some 
time should come to notice it.
</para>
<para>
Passions can be overcome by will checks. To resist
seduction, overcome fear etc, a will check is made,
modified by all suitable passions. Each passion adds
or subtracts to the roll, at its value x 5.
</para>

<para>
A +4 passion is beginning to consume your personality, 
and hence should come into play a lot of the time. 
Someone with a loyalty of +4 to someone, will obey 
that person without question except in situations 
which are obviously suicidal or go directly against 
the character's ethics. In these cases, the character 
may pause to think before obeying (or not).
</para>
<para>
A character with a +5 loyalty, will not even consider 
disobeying in the above cases, and if they do try to 
resist, the difficulty modifier is at +25.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Making Passion Checks</title>
<para>
Sometimes, a character will be in a situation where their 
passion will probably cause them to do something stupid, 
and the player may very well decide that they want their 
character to do something more sensible. In this case, a 
passion check may be required.
</para>

<para>
A passion check is rolled on straight will, with a modifier 
for any suitable passions. The difficulty will range from 
10 to 25.
</para>

