<sect2><title>Advantages and Disadvantages</title>
<para>
These are special bonuses and penalties characters can take 
to make them somewhat extraordinary compared to normal people.
</para>
<para>
The cost of all advantages and disadvantages taken must 
balance, and not all cost the same. The advantage of keen 
hearing which gives a small bonus to listening rolls, doesn't 
cost as much as the advantage of 'shape shifting' for example.
</para>
</sect2>
</sect1>


<sect1><title>Other Information</title>
<para>
Except where otherwise noted, the following standards can be 
assumed to be used throughout these rules:
</para>

<sect2><title>Fractions</title>
<para>
All fractions are rounded to the nearest whole number, and 
halves round up (away from zero).
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Weights and Measures</title>
<para>
The metric system is used throughout these rules, with metres 
and kilogrammes being the standard units of distance and weight.
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Money</title>
<para>
Because this version of the game system is geared towards 
fantasy, the monetary system used is based on Dark Ages 
England - the base unit of money is the silver penny (d), 
of which there are five to the shilling (s) and 240 to the 
pound (l). A pound is equivalent to a pound of silver in 
weight. Though there is no smaller denomination than the 
penny, a penny coin can be cut into halves or quarters.
</para>
</sect2>
</sect1>

